style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;"><font style="font-size: 22px;">Figure 1: Commercial Contracts as Criminal Law</font></h1><p>Whist there is nothing so corrupt as private wealth directly harnessing State Power for Enclosure Acts, there is still an effective and normalised route for the imposition of Private Tertiary Law by State authority. A commercial court enforces a private contract with Penal Notices. These are effectively equivalent to laws passed by the State, only directed at specific organisations or individuals. To breach a Penal Notice is a crime against the State, and hence punishments are commensurate, such as fines or imprisonment.</p>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="120" width="710" x="40" y="540" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;"><font style="font-size: 22px;">Figure 2: Trade Sovereignty</font></h1><p>This figure should by now look familiar.&nbsp; It shows how sovereignty is embodied in the supply, not the financial transaction. It doesn't matter where sovereignty lies in the value chain, because all the laws associated with the trade pass from the Seller to the Buyer.
